# Git Installation and Configuration Guide

This guide provides step-by-step instructions for installing and configuring Git on various platforms, along with essential configurations for software engineers.

## Installation

### Windows

#### Option 1: Git for Windows (Recommended)
1. Download the latest Git for Windows installer from https://gitforwindows.org/
2. Run the installer and follow the setup wizard
3. Choose components:
   - Git Bash
   - Git GUI
   - Git LFS
   - Associate .git* files
   - Associate .sh files
4. Choose default editor (VS Code recommended)
5. Adjust PATH environment: "Git from the command line and also from 3rd-party software"
6. Choose HTTPS transport backend: "Use the OpenSSL library"
7. Configure line ending conversions: "Checkout Windows-style, commit Unix-style line endings"
8. Configure terminal emulator: "Use Windows' default console window"
9. Configure extra options: Enable file system caching, Enable Git Credential Manager

#### Option 2: Chocolatey
```powershell
choco install git
```

#### Option 3: Winget
```powershell
winget install --id Git.Git -e --source winget
```

### Linux

#### Ubuntu/Debian
```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install git
```

#### CentOS/RHEL/Fedora
```bash
# CentOS/RHEL
sudo yum install git  # or dnf install git for newer versions

# Fedora
sudo dnf install git
```

#### Arch Linux
```bash
sudo pacman -S git
```

### macOS

#### Option 1: Xcode Command Line Tools
```bash
xcode-select --install
```

#### Option 2: Homebrew
```bash
brew install git
```

#### Option 3: MacPorts
```bash
sudo port install git
```



## Basic Configuration

### Global User Configuration
Set your name and email (required for commits):
```bash
git config --global user.name "Your Full Name"
git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"
```

### Check Configuration
```bash
git config --list
git config --global --list
```

### Default Editor
Set your preferred editor:
```bash
# VS Code
git config --global core.editor "code --wait"

# Vim
git config --global core.editor vim

# Nano
git config --global core.editor nano

# Sublime Text
git config --global core.editor "subl -n -w"
```

### Default Branch Name
Set default branch to 'main' (modern standard):
```bash
git config --global init.defaultBranch main
```

### Line Endings
Configure line ending handling:
```bash
# Windows
git config --global core.autocrlf true

# Linux/macOS
git config --global core.autocrlf input

# Disable (not recommended)
git config --global core.autocrlf false
```


### Diff and Merge Tools

#### Diff Tool (VS Code)
```bash
git config --global diff.tool vscode
git config --global difftool.vscode.cmd 'code --wait --diff $LOCAL $REMOTE'
```

#### Merge Tool (VS Code)
```bash
git config --global merge.tool vscode
git config --global mergetool.vscode.cmd 'code --wait $MERGED'
```

#### Diff Tool (Meld)
```bash
git config --global diff.tool meld
git config --global difftool.meld.cmd 'meld "$LOCAL" "$REMOTE"'
```

### Credential Helper
Store credentials securely:
```bash
# Windows
git config --global credential.helper manager-core

# macOS
git config --global credential.helper osxkeychain

# Linux
git config --global credential.helper store
# OR for more security
sudo apt install libsecret-1-0 libsecret-1-dev
cd /usr/share/doc/git/contrib/credential/libsecret
sudo make
git config --global credential.helper /usr/share/doc/git/contrib/credential/libsecret/git-credential-libsecret
```

## SSH Configuration

### Generate SSH Key
```bash
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your.email@example.com"
# OR for older systems
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -C "your.email@example.com"
```

### Configure SSH for Git
```bash
git config --global url."git@github.com:".insteadOf "https://github.com/"
```


### Check Git Version
```bash
git --version
```

### Update Git
```bash
# Windows: Download and install latest version

# Linux
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade git

# macOS (Homebrew)
brew upgrade git
```

### Clear Credentials
```bash
git config --global --unset credential.helper
```

### Reset Configuration
```bash
# Remove all global config
rm ~/.gitconfig

# Remove local config
rm .git/config
```


## Platform-Specific Notes

### Windows
- Use Git Bash for Unix-like commands
- Consider using Windows Terminal for better experience
- Be aware of line ending differences

### Linux
- Git is usually pre-installed on most distributions
- Use package managers for easy updates
- SSH keys work seamlessly

### macOS
- Xcode Command Line Tools include Git
- Homebrew provides latest versions
- SSH keys integrate well with Keychain

This guide covers the essential installation and configuration steps that every software engineer should know when working with Git.
